$$
\begin{bmatrix} 2 & 4 & 6 \\ 1 & 3 & 2 \\ 0 & 1 & 5 \end{bmatrix}
&\xrightarrow{R_1 \leftrightarrow R_2}
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 & 2 \\ 2 & 4 & 6 \\ 0 & 1 & 5 \end{bmatrix}
\quad \text{(sign changes)} \\
&\xrightarrow{R_2 - 2R_1}
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 & 2 \\ 0 & -2 & 2 \\ 0 & 1 & 5 \end{bmatrix}
\quad \text{(no change)} \\
&\xrightarrow{R_3 + \frac{1}{2}R_2}
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 & 2 \\ 0 & -2 & 2 \\ 0 & 0 & 6 \end{bmatrix}
\quad \text{(no change)}
$$
The determinant of the triangular matrix is $1 \cdot (-2) \cdot 6 = -12$.

Since we had one row interchange (which changes the sign):
$\det(A) = -(-12) = 12$.
